Runner Data Analysis

By: Aaron Stearns

This analysis is on athletic wearable device data. It is a timeseries dataset collected by a single runner over the course of a single workout.

There are many formatting issues and outliers in the data that need to be fixed or normalized before any meaningful analysis can take place, and Ill walk through those steps over the course of the project.

# Suite of tidy tools
library(tidyverse)
# Date formatting library
library(lubridate)
# Metric-Imperial conversion
library(udunits2)
# ML library with CART algorithm
library(rpart)

Functions

In this code block are the functions I wrote to create cumulative time/distance/elevation columns and convert strings to numeric values. The functions are designed to be used more than once on different columns of the data frame, thus following the software best practices of simplicity and DRY.

### Functions ##########################################################

# Splits minute/second strings in formats 01:32, 1:32, 1:32.4 and 01:32.4
# Returns total seconds as numeric (double) eg. "1:32.4" -> 92.4
convertToSeconds <- function(regexCleanedTime) { 
  splitTime <- unlist(str_split(regexCleanedTime, ":"))
  minutesToSeconds <- as.numeric(splitTime[1]) * 60
  seconds <- minutesToSeconds + as.numeric(splitTime[2])
  return(seconds)
}

# Function outputs a list of the incremented cumulative  
# value of any numerical column from the data frame. Used
# to create new cumulative value columns for time and distance
createIncrementingCumulative <- function(dataFrame, dataFrameColumn) {
  cumulativeList <- list()
  newVal <- 0
  
  for (i in 1:nrow(dataFrame)) {
    # Set starting index to first row value
    if (i == 1) {
      newVal <- dataFrame[i, dataFrameColumn]
      cumulativeList <- append(cumulativeList, newVal)
    }
    # Set each subsequent value to increment on previous
    else {
      newVal <- newVal + dataFrame[i, dataFrameColumn]
      cumulativeList <- append(cumulativeList, newVal)
    }
  }
  return(cumulativeList)
}

Time

This block of code formats the Time column in the data into a usable form, using several different regular expressions to parse and combine the digits in each observation. We can see in the output the newly created column, TimeInSeconds and its parsed values:

timeVector <- as.vector(unlist(data$Time))

# Loop uses regex to extract the minutes and seconds from each Time
# column observation and creates new column in the process
for (i in 1:length(timeVector)) {
  
  # This takes care of the row with erroneous value: 12:01:15 AM'
  if (str_count(timeVector[i], ":") > 1) {
    time <- str_extract(timeVector[i], "(?<=\\w{2}\\:)\\w{1,2}\\:\\w{1,2}\\.?\\w?")
    data$TimeInSeconds[i] <- convertToSeconds(time)
  } 
  # All other minute:second strings with and without partial seconds
  else {
    time <- str_extract(timeVector[i], "\\w{1,2}\\:\\w{1,2}\\.?\\w?")
    data$TimeInSeconds[i] <- convertToSeconds(time)
  }
}

The following loop replaces any improper punctuation in the Moving.Time column. One observation was 0"29 instead of 0:29.

for (i in 1:nrow(data)) {
  cleanTimes <- str_replace(data$Moving.Time[i], "[:punct:]{1}", ":")
  data$CleanMovingTime[i] <- convertToSeconds(cleanTimes)
}

Meters Per Second:

Now, to better understand the patterns in the runner data, Ill create a MetersPerSecond column.

for (i in 1:nrow(data)) {
  data$MetersPerSecond[i] <- (ud.convert(data$Distance[i], "mi", "km") * 1000) /    data$CleanMovingTime[i]
}

data %>% 
  select(Laps, Step.Type, MetersPerSecond) %>% 
  head()

## 1    1   warm up        2.942128
## 2    2   warm up        2.941215
## 3    3       run        3.978154
## 4    4   recover        3.056855
## 5    5       run        4.349578
## 6    6   recover        3.174896

The one missing value in the Step.Type column needs to be imputed. Im going to guess that this missing value is cool down based off of the fact that it is at the very end of the workout, it is preceded by a cool down value, and the meters per second between this observation and the previous observation are very similar.

# Include label for final row of Step.Type column 
data[data$Laps == nrow(data), 'Step.Type'] <- "cool down"

Machine Learning Bonus!

Just for fun, lets use the newly-created feature MetersPerSecond as a variable to predict the Step.Type of a given observation.

This will be a multi-class classification problem, with the dependent variable being Step.Type.

Ill use a simple CART (Classification And Regression Tree) with a training set of 80% of the observations to test on the remaining 20%

set.seed(1234)
train_index <- sample(nrow(data), nrow(data) * .8, replace = FALSE)
train <- data[train_index,]
test <- data[-train_index,]

# grow tree
treeFit <- rpart(Step.Type ~ MetersPerSecond,
             method="class", data=train)

# predict 'test' dataset values using trained model
prediction <- as.data.frame(predict(treeFit, test))

prediction$actual <- test$Step.Type

prediction
##    cool down recover   run warm up  actual
## 9      0.000   0.000 1.000   0.000     run
## 10     0.125   0.625 0.125   0.125 recover
## 11     0.000   0.000 1.000   0.000     run
## 12     0.125   0.625 0.125   0.125 recover
## 22     0.125   0.625 0.125   0.125 recover
## 23     0.000   0.000 1.000   0.000     run
## 30     0.125   0.625 0.125   0.125 recover

Here we can see the predicted probabilities of the observations of each Step.Type, with the far right column being the actual value, and the left-hand columns being the probabilities of the predicted class. Perfect accuracy!

Thoughts on additional features for machine learning:

Create isWarmup and isCooldown variables that check for increasing and decreasing meters per second speeds at the beginning and end of the dataset, respectively.
